===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|fr|en}} {{term|perche|lang=fr}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|pertica||staff”, “long pole”, “measuring rod|lang=la}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|es|perch}}

# a [[rod]], [[staff]], or [[branch]] of a [[tree]] etc used as a [[roost]] by a [[bird]]
#* Tennyson
#*: Not making his high place the lawless '''perch''' / Of winged ambitions.
# A [[pole]] connecting the fore gear and hind gear of a [[spring carriage]]; a [[reach]].
# a [[position]] that is [[secure]] and [[advantageous]], especially one which is [[prominent]] or [[elevated]]
# {{context|dated|lang=en}} a [[linear]] [[measure]] of 5½ [[yard]]s, equal to a [[rod]], a [[pole]] or ¼ [[chain]]; the related [[square]] measure
# a [[cubic]] measure of [[stonework]] [[equal]] to 16.6 × 1.5 × 1 [[feet]]
# {{context|textiles|lang=en}} a [[frame]] used to [[examine]] [[cloth]]

